INPUT:question:
Get all unique values in a JavaScript array (remove duplicates)
I have an array of numbers that I need to make sure are unique. I found the code snippet below on the internet and it works great until the array has a zero in it. I found this other script here on Stack Overflow that looks almost exactly like it, but it doesn't fail.
So for the sake of helping me learn, can someone help me determine where the prototype script is going wrong?
Array.prototype.getUnique = function() {
 var o = {}, a = [], i, e;
 for (i = 0; e = this[i]; i++) {o[e] = 1};
 for (e in o) {a.push (e)};
 return a;
}
More answers from duplicate question:
Remove duplicate values from JS array
Similar question:
Get all non-unique values (i.e.: duplicate/more than one occurrence) in an array

OUTPUT:answer:
The code you have posted uses an object-based approach to remove duplicates from an array. This approach works by adding each element in the array as a property of an object, which can only have unique properties. However, when an element is 0, this approach will not work as expected.

The reason is that when you add a property with a value of 0 to an object, it will be converted to a string and become "0", which is different from the original number 0. Therefore, when the second loop iterates over the properties of the object, it will include "0" in the result array, instead of 0.

To fix this, you can use the following code:

css

Array.prototype.getUnique = function() {
  var o = {}, a = [], i, e;
  for (i = 0; e = this[i]; i++) {
    o[e] = 1;
  }
  for (e in o) {
    a.push(+e);
  }
  return a;
};

Here, we use the unary plus operator (+) to convert the property back to a number before pushing it into the result array.

