Setting a bit means making it equal to 1. This can be done using the "OR" operator with a number that has only that bit set to 1.
Clearing a bit means making it equal to 0. This can be done using the "AND" operator with a number that has only that bit set to 0.
Toggling a bit means flipping its value, so it becomes 1 if it was 0, and vice versa. This can be done using the "XOR" operator with a number that has only that bit set to 1.

Here's an example in C:

c
Copy code
unsigned int set_bit(unsigned int num, int bit) {
    return num | (1u << bit);
}

unsigned int clear_bit(unsigned int num, int bit) {
    return num & ~(1u << bit);
}

unsigned int toggle_bit(unsigned int num, int bit) {
    return num ^ (1u << bit);
}
Note: bit is the position of the bit you want to set/clear/toggle (0-indexed). u in 1u << bit means an unsigned integer.

